x is 2^64 - 1, so we can't do that.\n    -- However, another observation is that in Lean, the components ofXX andYY are the squares of the components ofX andY modulo 2^64. Therefore, each component is < 2^64, but their sum is < 2^64 + 2^64 = 2^65. But in practice, perhaps they cannot both be 2^64 - 1 simultaneously, because the components ofX andY are bounded by 2^52.\n    -- Let's check:\n    -- (q.X[i]!) ≤ 2^52 implies (q.X[i]!)^2 ≤ (2^52)^2 = 2^104. However, in Lean, the square is taken modulo 2^64, so (XX[i]!) = (q.X[i]!)^2 % 2^64, which is ≤ (2^52)^2 % 2^64. But (2^52)^2 = 2^104, and 2^104 % 2^64 = 0 because 104 ≥ 64. So (XX[i]!) = 0 in this case.\n    -- This suggests that perhaps (XX[i]!) is always 0 for i < 5, but that's not true. For example, if q.X[i]! = 1, then (XX[i]!) = 1 % 2^64 = 1.\n    -- However, since (q.X[i]!) ≤ 2^52, then (q.X[i]!)^2 ≤ 2^104, and 2^104 = 2^64 * 2^40, so (q.X[i]!)^2 % 2^64 = 0 if (q.X[i]!)^2 < 2^64 * 2^40? No, actually, (q.X[i]!)^2 < 2^104, but 2^104 = 2^64 * 2^40, and (q.X[i]!)^2 modulo 2^64 could be up to 2^64 - 1. For example, if (q.X[i]!)^2 = 2^64 - 1, then the modulo would be 2^64 - 1. But (q.X[i]!)^2 = 2^64 - 1 is impossible if (q.X[i]!) ≤ 2^52, because (2^52)^2 = 2^104, and 2^64 - 1 < 2^104. However, maybe (q.X[i]!)^2 modulo 2^64 could be large.\n    -- Let's find a concrete case: suppose q.X[i]! = 2^32. Then (q.X[i]!)^2 = 2^64, and (XX[i]!) = 2^64 % 2^64 = 0. Not very helpful.\n    -- Another example: q.X[i]! = 2^32 + 1. Then (q.X[i]!)^2 = (2^32)^2 + 2*2^32 + 1 = 2^64 + 2^33 + 1, and (XX[i]!) = (2^64 + 2^33 + 1) % 2^64 = 2^33 + 1. Similarly, if q.Y[i]! = 2^32 + 1, (YY[i]!) = 2^33 + 1, and (YY[i]!) + (XX[i]!) = 2^34 + 2 ≤ U64.max, since 2^34 = 17179869184 and U64.max = 18446744073709551615. Actually, 2^34 + 2 = 17179869186 < 2^64 - 1.\n    -- It seems that in practice, because (q.X[i]!) ≤ 2^52, the sum (YY[i]!) + (XX[i]!) is actually ≤ 2^64 - 1 = U64.max.\n    -- How can we prove this? Note that (XX[i]!) = (q.X[i]!)^2 % 2^64, and (q.X[i]!)^2 ≤ (2^52)^2 = 2^104. So (q.X[i]!)^2 % 2^64 is the same as (q.X[i]!)^2 if (q.X[i]!)^2 < 2^64, otherwise it's (q.X[i]!)^2 - k * 2^64 for some k ≥ 1. But in any case, (XX[i]!) < 2^64.\n    -- The worst case for (XX[i]!) would be when (q.X[i]!)^2 is as large as possible but just below a multiple of 2^64. For example, (q.X[i]!) = 2^32, (q.X[i]!)^2 = 2^64, (XX[i]!) = 0. If (q.X[i]!) = 2^32 - 1, (q.X[i]!)^2 = 2^64 - 2^33 + 1, (XX[i]!) = 2^64 - 2^33 + 1 - 2^64 = -2^33 + 1 ≡ 2^64 - 2^33 + 1 mod 2^64, but in Lean, the modulo operation would make it 2^64 - 2^33 + 1, but we're storing it as a 64-bit unsigned integer, so it would be (2^64 - 2^33 + 1) % 2^64",
      "\n    intro i hi\n    have h₁ : (q.Y[i]!).val.le_127 := by\n      have : (q.Y[i]!).val ≤ 2 ^ 52 := h_qY_bounds i hi\n      omega\n    have h₂ : (q.X[i]!).val.le_127 := by\n      have : (q.X[i]!).val ≤ 2 ^ 52 := h_qX_bounds i hi\n      omega\n    have h₃ : ((q.Y[i]!).square[i]!).val ≤ 127 := by\n      have : (q.Y[i]!).val ≤ 127 := by\n        have : (q.Y[i]!).val.le_127 := h₁\n        exact le_of_lt_succ (by\n          omega\n          <;> norm_num)\n      have : ((q.Y[i]!).square[i]!).val ≤ 127 := by\n        have h₄ := ((q.Y[i]!).square[i]!).val.le_127\n        simpa [Nat.pow_succ, mul_assoc] using h₄\n      exact this\n    have h₄ : ((q.X[i]!).square[i]!).val ≤ 127 := by\n      have : (q.X[i]!).val ≤ 127 := by\n        have : (q.X[i]!).val.le_127 := h₂\n        exact le_of_lt_succ (by\n          omega\n          <;> norm_num)\n      have : ((q.X[i]!).square[i]!).val ≤ 127 := by\n        have h₄ := ((q.X[i]!).square[i]!).val.le_127\n        simpa [Nat.pow_succ, mul_assoc] using h₄\n      exact this\n    have h₅ : (YY[i]!).val = ((q.Y[i]!).square[i]!).val := by\n      have : YY = q.Y.square := by rfl\n      simp_all [FieldElement51]\n    have h₆ : (XX[i]!).val = ((q.X[i]!).square[i]!).val := by\n      have : XX = q.X.square := by rfl\n      simp_all [FieldElement51]\n    have h₇ : (YY[i]!).val + (XX[i]!).val ≤ 127 + 127 := by\n      omega\n    have h₈ : 127 + 127 ≤ U64.max := by\n      norm_num [U64.max]\n    omega",
      "\n    have h₁ : ∀ i < 5, (YY[i]!).val + (XX[i]!).val ≤ 2 ^ 64 - 1 := by\n      intro i hi\n      have h₂ : (q.X[i]!).val ≤ 2 ^ 52 := h_qX_bounds i hi\n      have h₃ : (q.Y[i]!).val ≤ 2 ^ 52 := h_qY_bounds i hi\n      have h₄ : (XX[i]!).val = (q.X[i]!).val ^ 2 := by\n        sorry\n      have h₅ : (YY[i]!).val = (q.Y[i]!).val ^ 2 := by\n        sorry\n      have h₆ : (XX[i]!).val ≤ (2 ^ 52) ^ 2 := by\n        sorry\n      have h₇ : (YY[i]!).val ≤ (2 ^ 52) ^ 2 := by\n        sorry\n      have h₈ : (YY[i]!).val + (XX[i]!).val ≤ (2 ^ 52) ^ 2 + (2 ^ 52) ^ 2 := by\n        sorry\n      have h₉ : (2 : ℕ) ^ 64 - 1 ≥ (2 ^ 52) ^ 2 + (2 ^ 52) ^ 2 := by\n        sorry\n      omega\n    sorry",
      "\n    intro i hi\n    have hx : (q.X[i]!).val ≤ 2 ^ 52 := h_qX_bounds i hi\n    have hy : (q.Y[i]!).val ≤ 2 ^ 52 := h_qY_bounds i hi\n    have hXX : (XX[i]!).val = (q.X[i]!).val * (q.X[i]!).val := by\n      rw [← XX_post]\n      <;> simp [Field51_as_Nat.mul, pow_two, Nat.ModEq]\n      <;>\n        norm_num [p] at *\n      <;>\n        ring_nf at *\n      <;>\n        simp_all [ModEq]\n      <;>\n        omega\n    have hYY : (YY[i]!).val = (q.Y[i]!).val * (q.Y[i]!).val := by\n      rw [← YY_post]\n      <;> simp [Field51_as_Nat.mul, pow_two, Nat.ModEq]\n      <;>\n        norm_num [p] at *\n      <;>\n        ring_nf at *\n      <;>\n        simp_all [ModEq]\n      <;>\n        omega\n    have h1 : (XX[i]!).val ≤ 2 ^ 104 := by\n      calc\n        (XX[i]!).val = (q.X[i]!).val * (q.X[i]!).val := by rw [hXX]\n        _ ≤ 2 ^ 52 * 2 ^ 52 := by\n          gcongr <;> simp_all\n        _ = 2 ^ 104 := by ring\n    have h2 : (YY[i]!).val ≤ 2 ^ 104 := by\n      calc\n        (YY[i]!).val = (q.Y[i]!).val * (q.Y[i]!).val := by rw [hYY]\n        _ ≤ 2 ^ 52 * 2 ^ 52 := by\n          gcongr <;> simp_all\n        _ = 2 ^ 104 := by ring\n    have h3 : (YY[i]!).val + (XX[i]!).val ≤ 2 ^ 104 + 2 ^ 104 := by\n      omega\n    have h4 : 2 ^ 104 + 2 ^ 104 ≤ U64.max := by norm_num [U64.max]\n    omega",
      "\n        norm_num [p] at *\n        <;>\n        ring_nf at *\n        <;>\n        omega\n      })\n    }) <;>\n    (try {\n      simp_all [FieldElement51_add, FieldElement51_mul, FieldElement51_sub, FieldElement51_two_mul, Field51_as_Nat_add, Field51_as_Nat_mul, Field51_as_Nat_sub, Field51_as_Nat_two_mul, p]\n      <;>\n      norm_num\n      <;>\n      omega\n    })\n  -- The rest of the proof follows directly from h₁\n  obtain ⟨c, hc⟩ := h₁\n  refine' ⟨c, hc.1, _⟩\n  simpa using hc.2",
